1 A JOINT RESOLUTION directing the Cabinet for Health and Family Services to
2 implement an in-home-drug disposal pilot program.
3 Be it resolved by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
4 ïƒ¢Section 1. (1) As used in this section:
5 (a) "Eligible patient" means an individual receiving a prescription for a Schedule
6 II controlled substance, including patients:
7 1. Who are at risk of experiencing an opioid-related overdose;
8 2. With an initial Schedule II controlled substance prescription;
9 3. With an acute Schedule II controlled substance prescription for a short-term
10 illness or condition; or
11 4. Who have received a change in dosage of an acute or chronic Schedule II
12 prescription;
13 (b) "In-home drug disposal system" means a site-of-use drug disposal system
14 that:
15 1. Changes the physical integrity of the formulation of the drug; and
16 2. Renders the active ingredients of a drug unusable for all practical purposes so
17 that it:
18 a. Is nontoxic and nonhazardous;
19 b. Poses no threat to the consumer;
20 c. Reduces drug exposure to the environment; and
21 d. Acts as a deterrent for misuse of the drug or drug formulation; and
22 (c) "Medication safety information" means any data tailored to meet the needs of
23 the patient population that is stored, processed, transmitted, or shared in person or in an
24 electronic format, including email, text message, image files, document files, or program
25 files, that includes but is not limited to:
26 1. In-home disposal of prescription drug medications;
27 2. Medication storage; and
